# 2. Semantic Tags

Semantic tags clearly describe the meaning of content.

### Why Use Semantic Tags?

* Better readability
* Better SEO
* Better accessibility
* Cleaner code

---

### Common Semantic Tags

#### Header

Top section of webpage.

```html
<header>
    <h1>My Website</h1>
</header>
```

#### Navigation

Navigation links.

```html
<nav>
    <a href="#">Home</a>
    <a href="#">About</a>
</nav>
```

#### Main

Main content area.

```html
<main>
    Content goes here
</main>
```

#### Section

Groups related content.

```html
<section>
    <h2>Services</h2>
</section>
```

#### Article

Independent content.

```html
<article>
    <h2>Blog Post</h2>
</article>
```

#### Aside

Sidebar or extra information.

```html
<aside>
    Related Links
</aside>
```

#### Footer

Bottom section of webpage.

```html
<footer>
    Copyright 2026
</footer>
```

---

# Semantic Layout Example

```html
<body>
    <header>
        <h1>My Website</h1>
    </header>

    <nav>
        <a href="#">Home</a>
        <a href="#">About</a>
    </nav>

    <main>
        <section>
            <article>
                <h2>Blog Title</h2>
                <p>Blog Content</p>
            </article>
        </section>

        <aside>
            Related Posts
        </aside>
    </main>

    <footer>
        Copyright 2026
    </footer>
</body>
```

### Interview Questions

1. What is the difference between `<div>` and semantic tags?
2. Difference between `<section>` and `<article>`?
3. Why are semantic tags important for SEO?
4. Difference between radio buttons and checkboxes?
5. What is the purpose of the `required` attribute?
6. Difference between GET and POST methods in forms?

Semantic tags give meaning to webpage content.
<div> is a generic container with no semantic meaning.
<section> groups related content; <article> is self-contained content.
Radio buttons allow one choice; checkboxes allow multiple choices.
required makes a form field mandatory.
GET sends data through the URL; POST sends data through the request body.

